%spark.pyspark
#before starting make sure you download the csv file containing all Landsat 8 scenes (wget https://landsat-pds.s3.amazonaws.com/scene_list.gz), gunzip it and rename it to a csv file and make it available on hdfs through a shell: hdfs dfs -put scene_list.csv /user/hadoop/scene_list.csv

%spark.pyspark
# 1) load this into a spark dataframe
df = spark.read.format("csv").option("header", "true").load("/user/hadoop/scene_list.csv")

%spark.pyspark
#2) check that the dataframe was correctly imported
df.show()

%spark.pyspark
#Cloudcover is the probability a pixel is covered by the clouds. What values do you expect? Are there any values outside of this range? Does the data contain duplicates?
#do a count before cleaning
df.count()
#this returns 1059757

%spark.pyspark
#now remove the duplicates and the cloudcovers with negative values
df = df.drop_duplicates()
df=df.filter(df["cloudCover"]>=0)
df.count()
#this leaevs us with 963826 records

%spark.pyspark
#Would it not be easy if we could just query on our data to get to know it better? Try to turn it in to a query-able format!
df.createOrReplaceTempView("scenes")

%spark.pyspark
#The landsat 8 project started in 2013. Since when do we have data? Does it look like all the files are here?
oldest_acquisition = spark.sql("SELECT min(acquisitionDate) FROM scenes ").show()
#oldest acquisitiondate is 2013-04-11, so this looks ok

%spark.pyspark
#It is hard to find good satellite pictures of Belgium...always so cloudy!! Find the least cloudy day in Belgium of the last 3 years
clear = spark.sql("SELECT download_url FROM scenes where  path='198' and row='24' order by cloudCover asc").show(1,False)
#the indexed image shows a compressed overviev of this clear day : https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/landsat-pds/L8/198/024/LC81980242015343LGN00/index.html
#and compare this to the most cloudy day!
cloudy = spark.sql("SELECT download_url FROM scenes where  path='198' and row='24' order by cloudCover desc").show(1,False)

%spark.pyspark
#Time for vacation...Select the average Cloudcover in Belgium and compare it to the one of the Costa Blanca. You can use for instance Benidorm's coordinates. 
df_BE= df[(df['path']==198) & (df['row'] == 25)]
df_CostaBlanca= df[(df['path']==198) & (df['row'] == 33)]
from pyspark.sql.functions import mean, min, max
df_BE.select([mean('cloudCover')]).show()
df_CostaBlanca.select([mean('cloudCover')]).show()

%spark.pyspark
#July in Belgium is the sunniest month averaging 7 hours of sunshine... Can you get the average cloudcover in the month of July for all data available 
spark.sql("SELECT avg(cloudCover) FROM scenes where  path='198' and row='24' and substring(acquisitionDate,6,2)='07' ").show(1)

%spark.pyspark
#In Southern California, two months (outside of the winter) are known to have a weather pattern that results in cloudy, overcast skies. This gives rise to appropriate nicknames for those months...Can you show the monthly average cloud covers, and find out what those two months are using the dataset available for the region around the city of San Diego?
month_avg=spark.sql("SELECT substring(acquisitionDate,6,2),round(avg(cloudCover)) FROM scenes where  path='40' and row='37' group by  substring(acquisitionDate,6,2) order by substring(acquisitionDate,6,2) asc")
month_avg.show()

%spark.pyspark
#check that the table exists now
conn.list_tables()

%spark.pyspark
#first change the schema names into something more readable
oldColumns = month_avg.schema.names
newColumns = ["month", "cloudavg"]
month_avg = reduce(lambda month_avg, idx: month_avg.withColumnRenamed(oldColumns[idx], newColumns[idx]), xrange(len(oldColumns)), month_avg)
month_avg.printSchema()
month_avg.show()

%spark.pyspark
#save the columns to a list that we will use to write the data to dynamo
months = month_avg.select('month').collect()
cloudavgs = month_avg.select('cloudavg').collect()

%spark.pyspark
#
import boto3
dynamodb = boto3.resource('dynamodb',region_name='eu-west-1')

%spark.pyspark
#now write all averages to the table
from datetime import datetime
with table.batch_writer() as batch:
    for i in range(12):
       rightnow = datetime.now()
       batch.put_item(Item={
        'User': 'Joris',
         'CreationTiming': str(rightnow),
         'cloudavg':str(cloudavgs[i][0]),
         'month':  months[i][0],
         'path' : '40', 
         'row' : '37'
     })

%spark.pyspark
#check that table contains the wanted items
response = table.scan()
items = response['Items']
print(items)

#show Antwerp picture
from numpy import *
from matplotlib.pyplot import *
from matplotlib.image import *
#import matplotlib.pylab as plot
import osgeo.gdal as gdal
from osgeo.gdalconst import *
def read_geotiff(filename, band_id=1):
   # Open the file
   dataset = gdal.Open( filename, GA_ReadOnly )
   if dataset is None:
      print 'Error: GDAL cannot open the file correct.'
      return None
   #fi
   # Fetch a band
   if (band_id < 1 | band_id > dataset.RasterCount):
      print 'Error: The specified band number is out of the range.'
      return None
   # fi
   band = dataset.GetRasterBand(band_id)
   # Get the Raster Data
   data = band.ReadAsArray(0, 0, dataset.RasterXSize, dataset.RasterYSize)
   # Close the file
   dataset = None  # the file will be closed when the dataset object is destructed
   return data
# end_def

resample_int = 4           # parameter for resampling the data because they are too large
filename = '/home/hadoop/JOB/data/L5198024_02420100906_B10.TIF'  # band 1 for TM and ETM+

data_blue = data_blue[::resample_int, ::resample_int]
filename = '/home/hadoop/JOB/data/L5198024_02420100906_B20.TIF'  # band 2
data_green = read_geotiff(filename)
data_green = data_green[::resample_int, ::resample_int]
filename = '/home/hadoop/JOB/data/L5198024_02420100906_B30.TIF'  # band 3
data_red = read_geotiff(filename)
data_red = data_red[::resample_int, ::resample_int]
(N, M) = data_blue.shape
data_rgb = zeros((N, M, 3), 'u1')
data_rgb[:, :, 0] = data_red.astype('u1')
data_rgb[:, :, 1] = data_green.astype('u1')
data_rgb[:, :, 2] = data_blue.astype('u1')
imshow(data_rgb,)
